        "# Problem 25: Differential Equations (Simplified)\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Solve the Following First-Order Ordinary Differential Equations\n",
        "\n",
        "### (a) $$ y'(x) = y(x) $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Rewrite the equation:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{dx} = y $$\n",
        "2. Separate variables:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{y} = dx $$\n",
        "3. Integrate both sides:\n",
        "   $$ \\ln|y| = x + C $$\n",
        "4. Solve for $$ y $$:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = Ce^x $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### (b) $$ y'(x) = \\frac{1}{2} y(x) $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Rewrite the equation:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{1}{2} y $$\n",
        "2. Separate variables:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{y} = \\frac{1}{2} dx $$\n",
        "3. Integrate both sides:\n",
        "   $$ \\ln|y| = \\frac{1}{2}x + C $$\n",
        "4. Solve for $$ y $$:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = Ce^{\\frac{1}{2}x} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Solve the First-Order ODEs Using Separation of Variables\n",
        "\n",
        "### (a) $$ \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{x}{y} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Separate variables:\n",
        "   $$ y \\, dy = x \\, dx $$\n",
        "2. Integrate both sides:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{y^2}{2} = \\frac{x^2}{2} + C $$\n",
        "3. Solve for $$ y $$:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = \\pm \\sqrt{x^2 + 2C} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### (b) $$ \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{y}{x} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Separate variables:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{y} = \\frac{dx}{x} $$\n",
        "2. Integrate both sides:\n",
        "   $$ \\ln|y| = \\ln|x| + C $$\n",
        "3. Solve for $$ y $$:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = Cx $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### (c) $$ \\frac{dy}{dx} = xy $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Separate variables:\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{dy}{y} = x \\, dx $$\n",
        "2. Integrate both sides:\n",
        "   $$ \\ln|y| = \\frac{x^2}{2} + C $$\n",
        "3. Solve for $$ y $$:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = Ce^{\\frac{x^2}{2}} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Solve the Second-Order Ordinary Differential Equations\n",
        "\n",
        "### (a) $$ y''(x) + y'(x) = 0 $$, with $$ y(0) = 2 $$ and $$ y'(0) = -1 $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Assume a solution of the form $$ y(x) = e^{rx} $$.\n",
        "2. Substitute into the equation:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 e^{rx} + r e^{rx} = 0 $$\n",
        "   Simplify:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 + r = 0 \\implies r(r + 1) = 0 $$\n",
        "   So, $$ r = 0 $$ or $$ r = -1 $$.\n",
        "3. General solution:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = C_1 e^{0x} + C_2 e^{-x} = C_1 + C_2 e^{-x} $$\n",
        "4. Apply boundary conditions:\n",
        "   - At $$ x = 0 $$, $$ y(0) = 2 $$:\n",
        "     $$ C_1 + C_2 = 2 $$\n",
        "   - At $$ x = 0 $$, $$ y'(0) = -1 $$:\n",
        "     $$ y'(x) = -C_2 e^{-x} \\implies y'(0) = -C_2 = -1 \\implies C_2 = 1 $$\n",
        "   - Substitute $$ C_2 = 1 $$ into the first equation:\n",
        "     $$ C_1 + 1 = 2 \\implies C_1 = 1 $$\n",
        "5. Final solution:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = 1 + e^{-x} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### (b) $$ y''(x) - y(x) = 0 $$, with $$ y(0) = 2 $$ and $$ y'(0) = 0 $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Assume a solution of the form $$ y(x) = e^{rx} $$.\n",
        "2. Substitute into the equation:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 e^{rx} - e^{rx} = 0 $$\n",
        "   Simplify:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 - 1 = 0 \\implies r = \\pm 1 $$\n",
        "3. General solution:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = C_1 e^{x} + C_2 e^{-x} $$\n",
        "4. Apply boundary conditions:\n",
        "   - At $$ x = 0 $$, $$ y(0) = 2 $$:\n",
        "     $$ C_1 + C_2 = 2 $$\n",
        "   - At $$ x = 0 $$, $$ y'(0) = 0 $$:\n",
        "     $$ y'(x) = C_1 e^{x} - C_2 e^{-x} \\implies y'(0) = C_1 - C_2 = 0 \\implies C_1 = C_2 $$\n",
        "   - Substitute $$ C_1 = C_2 $$ into the first equation:\n",
        "     $$ 2C_1 = 2 \\implies C_1 = 1 $$\n",
        "5. Final solution:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = e^{x} + e^{-x} $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### (c) $$ \\frac{d^2 y(x)}{dx^2} = -\\omega^2 y(x) $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Solution:\n",
        "1. Assume a solution of the form $$ y(x) = e^{rx} $$.\n",
        "2. Substitute into the equation:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 e^{rx} = -\\omega^2 e^{rx} $$\n",
        "   Simplify:\n",
        "   $$ r^2 = -\\omega^2 \\implies r = \\pm i\\omega $$\n",
        "3. General solution:\n",
        "   $$ y(x) = C_1 \\cos(\\omega x) + C_2 \\sin(\\omega x) $$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Check if $$ \\psi(t, x) = A \\cos(\\omega t + kx) $$ is a Solution of the Wave Equation\n",
        "\n",
        "The wave equation is:\n",
        "$$ \\frac{\\partial^2 \\psi}{\\partial t^2} - v^2 \\frac{\\partial^2 \\psi}{\\partial x^2} = 0 $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Step 1: Compute the Second Derivatives\n",
        "1. **Second derivative with respect to $$ t $$:**\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{\\partial^2 \\psi}{\\partial t^2} = -A\\omega^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx) $$\n",
        "2. **Second derivative with respect to $$ x $$:**\n",
        "   $$ \\frac{\\partial^2 \\psi}{\\partial x^2} = -Ak^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx) $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Step 2: Substitute into the Wave Equation\n",
        "$$ -A\\omega^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx) - v^2 (-Ak^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx)) = 0 $$\n",
        "Simplify:\n",
        "$$ -A\\omega^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx) + v^2 Ak^2 \\cos(\\omega t + kx) = 0 $$\n",
        "Factor out $$ A \\cos(\\omega t + kx) $$:\n",
        "$$ A \\cos(\\omega t + kx) (-\\omega^2 + v^2 k^2) = 0 $$\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Step 3: Conclusion\n",
        "For this to hold for all $$ t $$ and $$ x $$, the coefficient must be zero:\n",
        "$$ -\\omega^2 + v^2 k^2 = 0 \\implies v^2 = \\frac{\\omega^2}{k^2} $$\n",
        "Given $$ v = \\frac{\\omega}{k} $$, this condition is satisfied. Therefore, $$ \\psi(t, x) = A \\cos(\\omega t + kx) $$ is a solution of the wave equation.\n",
        "\n",
        "---"
